boone.util

Class StreamParser

  • java.lang.Object
    • boone.util.StreamParser

  • public class StreamParser
extends java.lang.Object
    Parse a stream, character by character. Provides read methods for various data types and read styles.

    The principle here is that the various read methods change the state of this parser object. For example, the readWord() method doesn't return a value, but sets the value of the workBuffer attribute instead.

    • Method Detail

      • nextChar

        public void nextChar()
        read the next character from the stream. Get the current character using the curChar variable. Error information is stored in the readState variable; -1 for End Of File, -2 for Exception, which is also stored in the readException variable, or a code >= 0 for OK.

      • getReadException

        public java.lang.Exception getReadException()

        remove whitespace from the end of the given StringBuffer

      • readSpaceOnly

        public void readSpaceOnly()
        Everything <= 32 is considered whitespace; this method reads over it. Doesn't read over comments (contrary to former readSpace behaviour). Uses nextChar(). Note that this function does not change the work buffer.

      • readSpace

        public void readSpace()
        Everything <= 32 is considered whitespace. Also reads over comments that start with commentStart and go until the end of the line. Uses nextChar(). Note that this function does not change the work buffer.

      • expect

        public boolean expect(java.lang.String str)
        expect some string.
        Returns:
        true iff the string did occur exactly as expected

      • readWord

        public void readWord()
        Read a word, until the next whitespace. If the current character is a whitespace, do nothing, and clear the workBuffer. The word that was read is put into the workBuffer.

      • readLine

        public void readLine()
        Read until the end of the line. A line terminates with a LF '\n' (but CRs '\r' are thrown away). Eats the '\n'. Puts the rest of the current line into the workBuffer, without the '\n', and without '\r's. Also, skips over a '\r' that follows the terminating '\n'.

      • readUntil

        public void readUntil(char ch)
        read until the given character occurs. The character is not consumed, i.e. it is not added to the workBuffer, but stays in the curChar variable.

      • readUntilCharOrNewline

        public boolean readUntilCharOrNewline(char ch)
        Read until the given character occurs, or until a Newline (LF, '\n') occurs. The character is not consumed, i.e. it is not added to the workBuffer, but stays in the curChar variable. Throws away all CRs '\r'.

        NOTE: This doesn't do exactly the same thing as readLine() - The curChar pointer remains at the final character (the given char, or NL). readLine, on the other hand, also eats the NL and possibly a following CR.

        Parameters:
        ch - The Char to read until.
        Returns:
        true, if the char was found; false, if a newline was encountered.

      • readIntNumber

        public int readIntNumber()
        Parse an integer number. Accept all characters in "0123456789-", Put the parsed number string into workBuffer, and also returns it.
        Returns:
        The parsed number, as an int.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NumberFormatException - if the parsed number is not a valid integer.

      • readFloatNumber

        public double readFloatNumber()
        Parse a floating-point number. Accept all characters in "0123456789-.Ee", Put the parsed number string into workBuffer.
        Returns:
        The parsed number, as a double.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NumberFormatException - if the parsed number is not a valid double.
